\f0\fs28 \cf0 THE MORAL FLOOR\
The strength of a republic rests not only on the design of its institutions but on the conduct of those who inhabit them. A nation can build its promises into law, engineer machinery capable of serving millions, and deliver real improvements in people\'92s lives, yet still lose its democratic character if the people entrusted with authority treat public power as a tool for private use. The Founders understood this tension, even if they did not solve it in full. They built a framework meant to withstand storms, but they assumed a baseline of integrity in the people who would hold it together. They believed ambition could be tempered by honor and that self-government would endure as long as those in office understood themselves as servants rather than masters. They placed more trust in civic virtue than in enforcement because they believed the two would rise together.\
That assumption was not na\'efve. In the early years of the republic, many who exercised power had already risked everything to secure the nation\'92s freedom. They saw public office as a limited stewardship, not a prize to be kept at all costs. Much of the system\'92s durability came not from the words on parchment but from the restraint of those who accepted its boundaries even when they might have pushed past them. The first peaceful transfer of power between rival factions did more to establish the tone of the republic than any clause in the Constitution. It signaled a belief that the nation was larger than any one person and that the republic\'92s survival depended on leaders enduring defeat with the same dignity as victory. These cultural guardrails, unwritten but widely shared, formed an invisible floor beneath the system. They held it up even when political pressures threatened to shake it.\
Over time, that floor grew thinner. Politics shifted from a temporary duty to a permanent career, and the temptations of office multiplied in step with its rewards. The expectation of good faith weakened as parties learned to treat every ambiguity in the law as an opening rather than a limit. Actions that once carried social consequences became routine. Public shame, once a powerful check on misconduct, lost its force in an environment where winning overshadowed everything else. The question that once guided public behavior\'97what is right for the republic\'97was replaced too often by a narrower one: what can we get away with. When that shift takes hold, the written rules of democracy are no longer enough to protect its substance, because they were never meant to carry the full load alone.\
A functioning republic requires more than compliance with law; it requires a shared ethical foundation strong enough to prevent the misuse of power even when the law is silent or slow to respond. That foundation is the moral floor. It is the baseline of conduct leaders must never fall below if the public is to trust that the system still works for them. It demands truthfulness in matters that shape public understanding, humility in the exercise of authority, and a willingness to place public duty above personal advancement. It requires a respect for democratic processes that does not evaporate when outcomes are inconvenient. It insists that the power of the state never be used as a weapon of personal retaliation and that opponents retain their rights even in the heat of political conflict. These expectations are modest. Yet without them the entire democratic structure begins to tilt.\
