\cf2 Beneath this baseline are six qualities that determine whether a democracy\'92s culture strengthens or decays. Character grounds the system in integrity, making it possible for leaders to act with consistency even when pressured to do otherwise. Ethics directs decisions toward the common good, keeping public office from becoming a tool for private gain. Restraint limits the reach of authority by ensuring that legality is not mistaken for necessity or wisdom. Truthfulness protects the shared reality on which democratic decisions rely, preventing power from rewriting facts to suit its needs. Good faith ensures that leaders honor not only the letter of rules but the democratic purposes behind them. Stewardship preserves institutions for those who follow, accepting the temporary nature of power and treating each office as a trust rather than a possession. When these qualities are present, democracy has an internal strength that no adversary can easily break. When even one collapses, the others begin to strain under the weight.\cf0 \
History\'92s lessons make this plain. Republics rarely fall because an enemy overpowers them; they fall because the habits that once held them upright erode a little at a time. Decay begins with leaders who treat ambition as destiny and public authority as fuel for personal projects. It deepens when citizens come to believe that such decay is inevitable or harmless, or that it is simply the cost of achieving political victories. The collapse is not sudden but cumulative. It is a gradual lowering of expectations until even serious breaches no longer shock the public conscience. By the time institutions strain under that load, the culture that once kept them steady has already thinned beyond recognition.\
For a modern democracy to recover, it must restore the moral floor with the same seriousness it brings to structural reform. A republic cannot be rebuilt only on new laws or updated machinery. It requires a culture in which restraint is expected, truthfulness is prized, and power is understood as a means of service. That work begins not with punishment but with clarity\'97naming the traits that allow a system to function and insisting that public office carry obligations that no victory can erase. The path forward includes stronger safeguards, but it also demands a civic norm that treats breaches not as clever strategy but as failure. A culture of accountability does not arise on its own. It is built by citizens who refuse to reward those who violate the public trust and by leaders who model a higher standard even when doing so costs them something.\
\cf2 This chapter sits at the heart of democratic repair. Structural reforms give the system shape and function, and the deliverables ensure that it meets the needs of the people. But without a moral floor, those gains cannot last. The Five Phases of renewal depend on a stable ethical foundation: one that prevents backsliding, strengthens public trust, and sets expectations that endure beyond any election cycle. It is the difference between a republic that survives on hope and one that survives on habits. For voters, the moral floor matters in the most personal ways. It determines whether the system treats people with dignity, whether rights are secure regardless of who holds office, and whether government remains accountable to the public will. It shapes the fairness of workplaces, the reliability of institutions, and the basic sense that the rules apply to everyone. A democracy with a strong moral floor protects not only its structure but the daily lives of those who depend on it.\cf0 \
\cf2 The way back begins here. A republic that restores its ethical foundation restores its confidence. A people who demand integrity in public life strengthen their own stake in self-government. And a system that expects leaders to honor the limits of their authority becomes resilient enough to endure the stresses ahead. Character, ethics, restraint, truthfulness, good faith, and stewardship are not abstractions. They are the conditions under which a free people can trust their own future. Strengthening them is not a moral luxury; it is the practical work of democratic survival.}